    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#robinson1913"/>, p. 178, n. <citedRange>48</citedRange> (without illustration)</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#Sammelbuch"/> <citedRange>5896</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI2"/>, p. 114, n. <citedRange>98</citedRange>, fig. 54</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.210</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>025400</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>137</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.73</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-64755"><name nymRef="#Κυρβασίας">Κυρβασίας</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65461"><name nymRef="#Πρᾶτις" type="patronymic">Πράτιος</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Kyrbasias fils de Pratis.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Kyrbasias son of Pratis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Kyrbasias figlio di Pratis.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Oliverio's provenance 'Necropolis' is only conjectural, as shown by De Cou's indication in <bibl><ptr target="#robinson1913"/></bibl>. Consequently, 
                    a family link with Pratis in <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr025300</ref> is quite uncertain as both bases might come from different places 
                    and not from a common family tomb. Without further arguments, the Thorns suspected that the provenance was the North Necropolis.</p>
	           <p>On the other hand a P<supplied reason="lost">rati</supplied>s son of Kyrbasias is mentioned in 320 BC in the <foreign rend="italic">diagramma</foreign> of 
	               Ptolemy (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr010800</ref>, l. 79) as being <foreign rend="italic">nomophylax</foreign>. The fact that the name Kyrbasias 
	               is very rare allows to consider that both mentions refer to one and the same person, rather than to grandfather and grandson.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
